<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-453-363  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 453 363.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 24 1990 v24 n39 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Auto club maps imaging route. (Auto Club of Southern Californiauses IBM's Imageplus electronic imaging storage and retrievalsystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bozman, Jean S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Auto Club of Southern California is installing IBM's Imagepluselectronic image storage and retrieval system to keep track of the600,000 insurance policies its members file yearly.andP;  Up to 45million documents in active files and 75 million in inactive filesneed to be accessible to the club's 80 branch offices.andP;  Theheadquarters office will use an IBM 3090 mainframe as a huge fileserver to contain images of documents that are processed byscanners and indexed on the IBM IMS database.andP;  Scanned images arestored in a jukebox optical drive and accessed by special PS/2 55computers with large display monitors.andP;  The acquisition ofImageplus equipment has cost the club over $3 million, but isexpected to save money in the long run.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Auto Club of Southern California (equipment and supplies)International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM ImagePlus (Image processing equipment) (usage)IBM PS/2 55 (Microcomputer) (usage)IBM 3090 400 (Mainframe computer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Imaging TechnologyImage processingStorage EquipmentCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>